Great spot for Solar Charge ....

They just charge 20 cents/kwh and still make 100% profit on the power. The security guard is very nice guy who "would not really notice" a non-employ in the L2 charge lot (20+ chargers/spots mostly empty!   There is also a L2 port at the east side of visitor lot but it is frequently used by EV employs for prime parking.
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx

Other nearby Nissan Leaf dealer charge info below:

I recommend  Davis Nissan for a better sales/customer service experience.   They not only offer free Chademo but want to come out and chat EV and help you plug in.

Both Roseville Future and Elk Grove nissan must be some of the worst dealers in California.  I recommend a free L2 charge on these facilities and spreading the word about Davis Nissan.


Roseville Future and Elk Grove  Nissan dealer does not seem to want to promote EVs.  They have sold rights of the ChAdeMo fast charge over to  EVgo.  It will cost you about 10$ per 50% charge.  What a bummer for leaf buyers who bought from these dealers.  They also offer man "plans" like AT&T at even more cost such as the $15/month plan with $29 cancelation fee;-(((

Elk Grove :  There are also only 4 spaces for 5 charges.  I had to block the ChadeMO so I could do a free L2 charge.

The sales manger was not really interested in any of my comments for creating and supporting his leaf customers.  They did have all these "customer appreciation event" signs in the lobby.  I guess it must be more about training for manager;-)

original:
Nissan NCTC

2015-05-10
Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps under their current design should have separate listings for L3s so that status (like under repair) and alerts (like all stations in use and station has become available) make sense for real human EV users.    
                                                 Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are failing to be honest in several ways:

0. Many stations are out of order, but not listed as such on the advertising posters in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for under repair. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of order but still using the normally working icon.

1. They do not provide 30-minute free sessions.

2. They fail to time the sessions for you.

3. They fail to cut off the session at 30 minutes.

4. If you go over, they charge you $7. This requires you to leave work or whatever you are doing, exactly in time to cut it off. If you leave too early, then you cut your session short. If you leave right on time, you must still cut your session a little short to avoid going over the 30 minutes on your own timing.

5. They refuse to document or provide measures for when the timer starts and when it ends.

6. When touch screens do not work, you cannot use NCTC over app or telephone. They say you can dispute it later, but their dispute process is opaque and time consuming. That is not a free 30-minute charge, either.

7. What they should have done, and what they probably originally meant to do, is simply provide $7 fast charges for free to NCTC customers.
augmented: Nissan NCTC2015-05-10Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps in their current design should have separate listings for L3s, so status (as in repair) and alarms (as in all stations that are in use and station has become available) make sense for real human users of electric vehicles. Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are not honest in several respects: 0. Many stations are out of service, but not listed as such on the billboards in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for repairs. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of service, but still use the normally functioning tool.1. They do not offer 30-minute free sittings.2. They fail to schedule the sessions for you.3. They do not interrupt the session after 30 minutes.4. If you pass, they charge you $7. This requires you to stop work or whatever you do just in time to exit them.

original: Chargepoint does not set the rates. The station owner does, in this case the mall. Until recently it was illegal to charge by the kWh in IL unless you area a utility. That's why by-the-hr pricing has been so common. But regardless, $2/hr is not a fair markup, it is a major gouge. That's 6 times the going rate for electricity with a 3.3 kW charger, 3 times the rate with a 6.6 kW charger. I have personally spoken to mall management on this matter, and they are apathetic. And your math is off for the mileage. A 6.6 kW charger will get you ~22 mi. Still cheaper than gas, but just barely. Not so for a 3.3 kW charger.
augmented: Until recently, it was illegal to charge per kWh in IL unless you have a utility, which is why hourly rates are so common, but regardless: $2 an hour is not a fair premium, it's a big chunk. That's 6 times the current price of electricity with a 3.3 kW charger, 3 times the price of a 6.6 kW charger. I've personally spoken to the management of the malls about this, and they're unapologetic, and your math is done in terms of mileage. A 6.6 kW charger will take you about 22 miles. Even cheaper than gas, but scarce. Not so with a 3.3 kW charger.

original: TESLA OWNERS - MODEL S UPGRADE - They have a brand new cable, Model S adapter and the Tesla approved socket to plug it into. With 40 amps, charged my P85D at 25 mi/hr. I arrived at 1:30am after 16 hours of driving (and charging).  Dario, the night welcomer in chief was so gracious. He got out the brand new Tesla cable and adapter and then, with his cell phone light, got it plugged into the Castle & connected the car. Full charge this morning!  Plus charger is at back of one of the two handicap spaces right next to the front door.  You have to be a guest but there's really nowhere else to go once you drive up the long drive to the top of the hill. GREAT destination connection though, as dinner guests at Equus often linger up to 4 hours so that's 100 extra miles if you need it (or just top off) or a full charge every night if you're staying here.  The staff is helpful and knowledgable - really top notch. Come on MODEL S OWNERS lets lobby to get a couple of the 100amp home chargers in here like the places along the west coast that have MADE themselves destinations for Model S owners, convenient and comfortable for the only long distance, fast and fun, total EV made (just drove from OR to San Fransisco, to here, NYC, 4500 miles + in new P85D in less then two weeks - home to north of Boston tomorrow).  Thank you PlugShare members who added crucial extra info to charging locations - I couldn't have made it without you. If you want to travel north of Boston my home charger will be listed tomorrow, and welcome.
augmented: TESLA OWNERS - MODEL S UPGRADE - You have a brand new cable, Model S adapter and Tesla-approved outlet to connect to. I charged my P85D at 40 amps at 25 miles per hour. Dario, the senior night owl, was so gracious, he took out the brand new Tesla cable and adapter and then brought it into the lock with his cell phone light and connected the car. You have to be a guest, but there really is no other way to take the long drive up the hill. GREAT destination connection, although as a dinner guest at Equus you often stay up to 4 hours, so that's 100 extra miles if you need it (or just get one on top).

original: As a summer intern at Holman Cadillac in Mount Laurel, I've been looking for ways to improve our communication with clients about what it's like to own an EV, and to ease some of the common concerns potential buyers have. I tried to gain insight by taking the Cadillac ELR to all of the public charging stations in the local South Jersey area and judging the ease of use and abundance of stations over specific areas. This station had an affordable $5 nominal fee and was housed near the Chapel Ave side main entrance to the complex. Equipped with two spaces and two chargers, this station is within walking distance to the Cherry Hill Mall, Loews Movie Theater, and several other restaurants and attractions. www.holmancadillac.com

At an affordable price of $5, this station was located near the Chapel Ave side entrance. original: I stopped by this site to check it out, because it had been showing up as busy in the Chargepoint system for WEEKS.  Every time I looked it showed busy.  When I got there a Ford Fusion Energi was plugged in, and according to the EVSE it had been plugged in for nearly 10 hours, and was obviously fully charged.  As I was there the owner walked up to leave and said he and another local worker (with a Nissan Leaf) are tag teaming on the charger, so it will frequently indicate busy.  However if they are charged up you should be OK to unplug.  I gave him a printed copy of the *excellent* PlugInAmerica charging etiquette dashboard card ( http://www.pluginamerica.org/evcard ) so he can indicate to other EV arrivals that they can unplug him.  I also left some more cards at the station.
augmented: When I got there, a Ford Fusion Energi was hooked up, and according to EVSE, it had been hooked up for almost 10 hours and apparently fully charged. However, if they are charged, you should be fine to pull the plug off. original: Relaying another checkin from a friend ... With his Model S cord and the NEMA 14-50 receptacle, he found that his charging cable got quite hot.  Typically this is because of a bad wiring connection somewhere, and could be in the receptacle not the cord (with the excess heat then flowing from the receptacle to the cord through the wiring metal).  For that reason some Tesla Model S owners have been backing off the current draw, say down to 25 Amps.  He did that, overnight, and got a full charge.
augmented: With his Model S cable and NEMA 14-50 socket, he found that his charging cable was getting pretty hot. Typically, this is due to a poor wiring connection somewhere and could be in the socket, not the cable (where the excess heat then flows from the socket through the wiring metal to the cable), which is why some Tesla Model S owners have withdrawn the power, say to 25 amps. He did so overnight and got a full charge.

original: We attended the, "Odyssey of the Mind" event last Saturday. I had charged my Tesla up to 90% at the Double Tree hotel but needed a full range charge to comfortably get back to Buffalo. I had contacted Ms. Susan Crane, the Parking Services Director via email (scrane@binghamton.edu) about a week prior to the event and asked for access to the chargers in the ramp D parking garage. I was given an access code to input into the keypad of a specific charger. At the gate to the ramp the attendant had received a copy of the info needed to get me access and I connected without a problem. Later that evening, we returned home with 24 miles on the battery. Paid the $6 event parking fee. Charger was otherwise free. 30A@208V. Very shortly the issue will be less compelling since the Syracuse Supercharger should be online in a week.

At the gate to the ramp, the employee had received a copy of the information needed to access my chargers, and I connected without any problems. Upon my return a few days later, they brought the car out to me, all charged up. The other places nearby are Level 1 and you might not get a spot.  You pay a little more here but it may be worth it to you if you need a full charge to make it back home.

Note to admins:  when I added this location, I had been told that there were two dual-plug charging sites.  Each site actually has only one plug; please remove the extra plugs in this database record.

This is currently the only Level 2 that is charged near the airport, and the best place to go to guarantee that you will receive a charge. The other locations nearby are Level 1 and you may not get a seat. original: Talked our way into this garage earlier today on our EV roadtrip through Maryland. This was our planned charging stop for the O's-Nats game at Camden Yards. Parking guy near the entrance waived us away indicating it was for permit holders only. Gave 'em the "we came all the way from West Virginia to watch the O's and we won't make it home if we can't charge" story (which was true LOL!), so he went and talked to his Supervisor who promptly waved us in. My feeling? On weeknights and weekends, if you talk nice and explain you're driving an EV, they'll likely let you charge. Just tell 'em you drove all the way from West Virginia :-) Not sure the sob story would work 9am-5pm during the week though. Volt owner we talked to (who works there and plugs-in regularly), said all of the charging spaces are often filled during the workday. Great location though if you can get in!
augmented: This was our scheduled charging stop for the O's Nats game in Camden Yards. The parking lot type near the entrance waived us, saying it was for privilege holders only. My feeling? On weekdays and weekends, if you talk nicely and declare that you're driving an electric car, they'll probably let you charge up. Just tell us you drove all the way from West Virginia: -) Not sure if the sobbing story would work between 9 a.m. and 5 p.m. during the week.
